<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30048191.260538/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMjEva2VlcGluZy10cmFjay1vZi1jcnlwdG8taXMtaGFyZD9jbXBpZ=
D1CQkQxMjIxMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xl=
dHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEyMjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmYjZm9vdG5vdGUtMw/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3f073ecf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  think often</a> about the time=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30048191.260538/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDItMTQvanBt=
b3JnYW4taGFzLWEtY29pbi1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl=
1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYW=
lnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB38c90559" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I wrote</a>=
:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you have U.S. dollars in a bank=
 account at JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co., and I have U.S. dollars in a bank acc=
ount at JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co., and I want to send you 100 of my dollars,=
 what we do is I tell JPMorgan to subtract 100 from the number of dollars i=
n my bank account and add 100 to the number of dollars in your bank account=
. This gets dressed up in a lot of=C2=A0<em>procedures</em>, because it wou=
ld be bad if JPMorgan got the math wrong or if it moved money from one acco=
unt to another without getting the proper authorizations, but as a matter o=
f, like, computer science, it is dead easy. JPMorgan keeps a list of people=
 and how many dollars they have, and you and I both trust JPMorgan=C2=A0to =
keep that list (that=E2=80=99s what it means that we bank there!), and so w=
e just tell JPMorgan to update the list to reflect the transaction between =
us.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And lots of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30048191.260538/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9tYXR0X2xl=
dmluZS9zdGF0dXMvMTA5NjExOTc1NDI4MzI3ODM0MQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd779c7d=
d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> computer engineers</a>=C2=A0tweeted and emailed to be like =
=E2=80=9Cno, actually, it is a hard problem of computer science to have a b=
ig database of who has what, and to update it instantly and reliably to ref=
lect transactions from many different sources.=E2=80=9D And I was like, sur=
e, fine, I guess. I still feel like I was=C2=A0<em>entitled=C2=A0</em>to be=
 right: A bank is, at its heart, a computer for keeping track of who has mo=
ney, and for updating its ledger as people send and receive money. And at a=
 high level you and I could describe how we=E2=80=99d expect that computer =
to work =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cif I deposit $100 in an ATM, the bank will =
increase the number in my account by $100,=E2=80=9D that sort of thing =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and we will be disappointed if it doesn=E2=80=99t work that way=
, if the bank loses track of who has the money or how much they have, or if=
 it doesn=E2=80=99t update its ledger promptly or process transactions in t=
he right order. If the bank messes up and says =E2=80=9Clook I am sorry but=
 keeping track of money is a hard job and you can=E2=80=99t expect us to do=
 it with 100% accuracy,=E2=80=9D we will say things like =E2=80=9Cyes we ca=
n=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthat is literally exactly what we expect of you=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cif keeping track of the money=C2=A0is too hard for you =
then maybe you should not be a bank=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cnow you have to p=
ay an enormous fine.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And yet, sure, empirically, banks do som=
etimes mess it up. It=E2=80=99s not as easy as it sounds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wells Fargo, for instance,=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30048191.260538/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Y29uc3VtZXJmaW5hbmNlLmdvdi9hYm91dC11cy9uZXdzcm9vbS9jZnBiLW9yZGVycy13ZWxscy1=
mYXJnby10by1wYXktMzctYmlsbGlvbi1mb3Itd2lkZXNwcmVhZC1taXNtYW5hZ2VtZW50LW9mLW=
F1dG8tbG9hbnMtbW9ydGdhZ2VzLWFuZC1kZXBvc2l0LWFjY291bnRzLw/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBa804d300" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">messes it up a lot</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Consumer Financial Protection =
Bureau (CFPB) is ordering Wells Fargo Bank to pay more than $2 billion in r=
edress to consumers and a $1.7 billion civil penalty for legal violations a=
cross several of its largest product lines. The bank=E2=80=99s illegal cond=
uct led to billions of dollars in financial harm to its customers and, for =
thousands of customers, the loss of their vehicles and homes. Consumers wer=
e illegally assessed fees and interest charges on auto and mortgage loans, =
had their cars wrongly repossessed, and had payments to auto and mortgage l=
oans misapplied by the bank. Wells Fargo also charged consumers unlawful su=
rprise overdraft fees and applied other incorrect charges to checking and s=
avings accounts. Under the terms of the order, Wells Fargo will pay redress=
 to the over 16 million affected consumer accounts, and pay a $1.7 billion =
fine, which will go to the CFPB's Civil Penalty Fund, where it will be used=
 to provide relief to victims of consumer financial law violations.</p></bl=
ockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the CFPB=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30048191.260538/aHR0cHM6Ly9maWxlcy5jb=
25zdW1lcmZpbmFuY2UuZ292L2YvZG9jdW1lbnRzL2NmcGJfd2VsbHMtZmFyZ28tbmEtMjAyMl9j=
b25zZW50LW9yZGVyXzIwMjItMTIucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9da7fee9" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> consent order</a>=C2=A0from yesterday, which is basically just a litany o=
f =E2=80=9CWells Fargo=E2=80=99s computers messed up.=E2=80=9D For instance=
:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Respondent also assessed borrowers=
 erroneous fees and interest because of technology, audit, and compliance f=
ailures. As an example, from at least 2011 until at least March 2019, Respo=
ndent sometimes incorrectly entered the effective date of a payment deferme=
nt in, or omitted it from, its servicing system-of-record, which resulted i=
n $26.5 million in erroneously assessed late fees to more than 688,000 borr=
ower accounts.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you owe Wells Fargo money on a car loan, an=
d you don=E2=80=99t pay it, and you have a payment deferment, they won=E2=
=80=99t charge you a fee, but if you don=E2=80=99t have a payment deferment=
 they will. But if you have a payment deferment, but they don=E2=80=99t wri=
te it down in the right place, they will also charge you the fee, and then =
they will get in trouble. In some sense this is profit-maximizing behavior =
by Wells Fargo: If they agree to defer payments, and then charge you the fe=
es anyway, they will make more money in fees. But it doesn=E2=80=99t seem=
=C2=A0<em>intentional</em>, and the CFPB doesn=E2=80=99t think it was. (Why=
 <em>say=C2=A0</em>you agree to the deferment, and then charge the fees?) I=
t seems like a failure of systems, of =E2=80=9Ctechnology, audit and compli=
ance=E2=80=9D: Wells Fargo did not do a good job of keeping track of deferm=
ents, so it sometimes charged fees by mistake.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From at least 2011 through 2022, R=
espondent experienced other types of servicing errors, which had the potent=
ial to contribute to a borrower=E2=80=99s delinquency, and in some cases le=
d to improper repossessions. For example, Respondent repossessed vehicles d=
espite the borrower having made a payment or entering into an agreement to =
forestall the repossession.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are delinquent on a car loan to Wells F=
argo, eventually some system at Wells Fargo decides to repossess your car. =
There is some delay between when this system sets the repossession in motio=
n=C2=A0and when someone actually takes the car. In the meantime, if you mak=
e a payment, or sign an agreement with some other person at Wells Fargo to =
avoid repossession, then some other=C2=A0system at Wells Fargo knows that W=
ells Fargo should not repossess your car. Do those systems talk to each oth=
er? Does the person signing the agreement, or the mailbox receiving your pa=
yment, have a way to stop the repossession that is lurching into motion? Me=
h, sometimes, maybe, but not all the time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, this does not seem like rational profit=
-maximizing behavior by Wells Fargo; repossessing the car is surely more of=
 a pain than having the borrower start making payments again. No one at Wel=
ls Fargo was like =E2=80=9Cbwahahaha, a clever trick would be to repossess =
people=E2=80=99s cars even after they start paying their loans back.=E2=80=
=9D Wells Fargo just did it anyway. It is an emergent feature of Wells Farg=
o=E2=80=99s bureaucracy, and its computers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Guaranteed Asset Protection (GAP) =
contracts are a type of debt cancellation contract (DCC) that generally rel=
ieve the borrower from the obligation to pay the remaining amount of the bo=
rrower=E2=80=99s loan on the vehicle above the vehicle=E2=80=99s depreciate=
d value in the case of a major accident or theft. The auto dealer markets G=
AP coverage to the borrower=C2=A0and is paid the GAP fee. However, borrower=
s often finance GAP fees as part of their auto loan at origination and the =
GAP contract becomes part of the auto loan contract. If the borrower pays o=
ff the loan early, or the GAP contract otherwise terminates, the borrower m=
ay be entitled to a refund of the unearned portion of the GAP fee that they=
 financed when first buying the vehicle. Such refund obligations usually ar=
e governed by the terms of the GAP contract executed between the borrower a=
nd the originating dealer, with GAP contracts sometimes requiring that the =
borrower make a written request to the originating dealer for a GAP refund.=
 Respondent, as the owner and servicer of the GAP contracts, did not ensure=
 that unearned GAP fees were refunded to all borrowers who paid off their l=
oans early.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is just, like, Wells Fargo entered into a=
 complicated contract with its auto-loan borrowers, and the contract provid=
ed that in certain circumstances, years in the future,=C2=A0Wells Fargo wou=
ld have to send some money to the borrowers, and Wells Fargo just stuck the=
 contract in a drawer somewhere and ignored it, and so did the borrowers, s=
o it never sent them the money. Very understandable, for the borrowers, who=
 are busy people who have jobs and lives and are not necessarily reading ev=
ery word of their auto-loan contracts. Less understandable, for the bank, w=
hich is a bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another error occurred from July 2=
013 until September 2018, when Respondent did not offer no-application modi=
fications to approximately 190 borrowers with Government Sponsored Entity (=
GSE) loans. Respondent=C2=A0erroneously identified these borrowers as decea=
sed and therefore did not assess their eligibility for modifications. Respo=
ndent is paying approximately $2.4 million in remediation to these borrower=
s.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is a little hard to tell how that one would=
 work? Like, the rule is something like =E2=80=9Ccertain mortgage borrowers=
 need to be offered this loan modification.=E2=80=9D Wells Fargo went throu=
gh its records to see who needed to be offered the modification, and decide=
d not to offer it to these 190 people because they were dead. They were not=
 dead, so, a failure of record-keeping by Wells Fargo. But also =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0they were not offered the modification, so they kept paying their mor=
tgages?<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Like every month Wells Fargo would get a check from these people =
whom it had erroneously identified as deceased? If=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>g=
ot a check every month from someone who you thought was dead, you would be =
surprised, and presumably you would update your views. (You might think =E2=
=80=9Caha, they are <em>not </em>dead,=E2=80=9D or you might think =E2=80=
=9Cwow ghosts are real and very financially responsible,=E2=80=9D or you mi=
ght <em>call=C2=A0</em>them to say =E2=80=9Cso are you dead or what?=E2=80=
=9D)=C2=A0But Wells Fargo is not a human with normal human intuitions. It i=
s a big bureaucratic institution with databases that don=E2=80=99t necessar=
ily talk to each other in sensible ways, and it blithely went along cashing=
 checks from people while also believing they were dead.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are CFPB Director Rohit Chopra=E2=80=99s =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30048191.260538/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29uc3VtZXJmaW5hbmNlLmdvdi9hYm91dC11cy9uZXdzcm9vbS9wcmVwYXJlZ=
C1yZW1hcmtzLW9mLWNmcGItZGlyZWN0b3Itcm9oaXQtY2hvcHJhLW9uLXRoZS13ZWxscy1mYXJn=
by1sYXctZW5mb3JjZW1lbnQtYWN0aW9uLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfacd3d83" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> remarks on the enforcement action</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the CFPB=E2=80=99s eleven years of existenc=
e, Wells Fargo has consistently been one of the most problematic repeat off=
enders of the banks and credit unions we supervise. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Put simply, Wells Fargo is a corporate recidiv=
ist that puts one third of American households at risk of harm. Finding a p=
ermanent resolution to this bank=E2=80=99s pattern of unlawful behavior is =
a top priority. Today, CFPB is announcing an important step toward that goa=
l: restitution for victims of Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s widespread illegal acti=
vities. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While today=E2=80=99s order addresses a number=
 of consumer abuses, it should not be read as a sign that Wells Fargo has m=
oved past its longstanding problems or that the CFPB=E2=80=99s work here is=
 done. Importantly, the order does not provide immunity for any individuals=
, nor, for example, does it release claims for any ongoing illegal acts or =
practices.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While $3.7 billion may sound like a lot, the C=
FPB recognizes that this alone will not fix Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s fundament=
al problems. Over the past several years, Wells Fargo executives have taken=
 steps to fix longstanding problems, but it is also clear that they are not=
 making rapid progress. We are concerned that the bank=E2=80=99s product la=
unches, growth initiatives, and other efforts to increase profits have dela=
yed needed reform.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Imagine being the sort of person who gets ahea=
d in banking and becomes a senior executive at Wells Fargo. One of your sub=
ordinates comes to you to be like =E2=80=9CI have an idea for a new product=
 that will attract a lot of customers and bring in a lot of revenue.=E2=80=
=9D Another one of your subordinates comes to you to be like =E2=80=9Csomet=
imes we charge people late fees even after agreeing not to, because our sys=
tems don=E2=80=99t talk to each other very well; I have an idea for how to =
modernize them to make sure that doesn=E2=80=99t happen. It will cost a lot=
 of money, but in exchange we, uh, won=E2=80=99t get to charge as many late=
 fees?=E2=80=9D Which subordinate would you want to spend more time with? W=
ho sounds like more fun?</p>
